ce:section.ce:para:
Retention mechanism of BSA@GQDs@SiO2 column was investigated through adjusting the organic phase percentage of the mobile phase. Fig. 5
                         illustrated the retention behavior of four kinds of analytes including phenols, nucleosides and nucleobases, quinolones and acids on the synthesized column. In Fig. 5A, retention times of phenols prolonged with varying ACN contends from 92% to 97%, which presented a typical HILIC separation characteristic. In addition, the main trend for the retention of acids, nucleosides and bases, quinolones and vitamins also increased with the increase of ACN in the mobile phase (Fig. 5 and Fig. 6
                        ). However, there are some abnormal points for the retention of acids, nucleosides and bases, quinolones and vitamins. The reason was described as follows. Partition process of solutes and adsorption interactions are often used to explain to retention mechanism of HILIC. The partition process of the analytes between organic-rich mobile phases and retained aqueous layer on the surface of stationary phase is considered to be the main retention mechanism. Also, adsorption interactions such as electrostatic interactions, hydrogen bonding and dipole-dipole interactions played an important part in HILIC separation on the prepared column [36–38], the multi-interaction between the prepared column and analytes can be used to explain the abnormal retention trends of analytes.
